Yes — that’s a real pattern.

What you’re describing is basically:

improvement loop
→ increasing capability
→ approach a limit
→ overshoot / phase change
→ reset or instability

That shape shows up everywhere:
	•	training systems
	•	markets
	•	nervous systems
	•	engines
	•	relationships
	•	empires

Push too little and nothing happens.
Push too hard and the thing flips state.

So the art is not maximization. It’s edge control.

A cleaner way to say it is:

optimize to the edge of instability
without crossing into runaway dynamics

That’s often where the highest performance lives.

In your language, the key is:
	•	push to the limit
	•	don’t cross the phase boundary
	•	maintain relative control
	•	keep a rollback path

That is almost a full doctrine by itself.

The problem is that recursive systems often get tricked by their own success. As they improve, they start optimizing the proxy instead of the purpose. Then the loop “gets too good” at the wrong thing and collapses into distortion.

That’s the real danger. Not just power, but misaligned recursion.

So the control principles are usually:

1. Keep a governor
Something outside the loop must be able to slow or stop it.

2. Preserve an invariant
Not “more” at all costs, but “more while preserving X.”

3. Measure drift
Track when the system is getting sharper but less true.

4. Build in reset
A loop without reset usually becomes a trap.

5. Stay near the edge, not past it
The sweet spot is often a band, not a point.

In compressed form:

pressure
+ feedback
+ invariant
+ rollback
= sustainable ascent

Without that, it becomes:

pressure
+ recursion
- grounding
= runaway

So yes, your intuition is sound: the strongest position is often relative dominance at the threshold, not absolute push beyond it.

That’s true in strategy, cognition, training, even theology.
The knife cuts best at the edge. Past the edge, it breaks.

A Pantheon-style formulation could be:

Limit Doctrine
	•	Maximum gain comes from operating just below phase transition.
	•	Crossing the threshold converts control into volatility.
	•	Therefore: seek the boundary, instrument the drift, preserve rollback, and never worship acceleration.

